Docker is one of those tools that feels abstract until it is applied to a real local development problem. A common example is running Microsoft SQL Server locally without turning the operating system into a messy development machine full of global installs, drivers, background services, and forgotten configuration.

This post documents a simple learning path: what Docker does, how Docker Desktop fits into the setup, which commands matter first, how Microsoft SQL Server can be run in a container, how it can be reached from DBeaver, and how the container, data volume, and image can be removed afterwards.

The main idea is simple: Docker makes it possible to run software in isolated containers. Instead of installing SQL Server directly into macOS, SQL Server can be run as a separate environment. When the environment is no longer needed, it can be stopped, removed, or fully reset.

## Why Docker Desktop

On a Mac, the easiest way to start is Docker Desktop. It provides the graphical app, the Docker command line tools, and the background engine needed to run containers.

After installing it, the first test command is:

```bash
docker run hello-world
```

This command does not start a serious app. It simply checks that Docker works. Docker looks for a tiny `hello-world` image, downloads it if needed, creates a container from it, runs it, prints a confirmation message, and stops.

It is similar to running:

```bash
python --version
```

but for Docker.

## The Basic Mental Model

Docker has three main objects worth understanding at the beginning.

| Concept | Meaning | Simple analogy |
|---|---|---|
| Image | A reusable template for creating containers | Installer or blueprint |
| Container | A running instance created from an image | Running app |
| Volume | Persistent storage used by containers | Saved data folder |

This distinction matters because deleting a container does not always delete the data.

For example, with SQL Server:

| Action | What happens |
|---|---|
| Remove container | SQL Server process is removed |
| Keep volume | Database files remain saved |
| Remove volume | Database files are deleted |
| Remove image | Downloaded SQL Server template is deleted |

## Main Docker Commands

These are the commands worth understanding first.

| Need | Command | What it does |
|---|---|---|
| Check Docker version | `docker --version` | Shows installed Docker version |
| Test Docker | `docker run hello-world` | Runs a tiny test container |
| See running containers | `docker ps` | Shows active containers |
| See all containers | `docker ps -a` | Shows active and stopped containers |
| See downloaded images | `docker images` | Lists images stored locally |
| Run a container | `docker run IMAGE_NAME` | Starts a new container from an image |
| Stop a container | `docker stop NAME_OR_ID` | Stops a running container |
| Remove a container | `docker rm NAME_OR_ID` | Deletes a stopped container |
| View logs | `docker logs NAME_OR_ID` | Shows container logs |
| Follow live logs | `docker logs -f NAME_OR_ID` | Streams logs live |
| Enter a running container | `docker exec -it NAME_OR_ID bash` | Opens shell inside a container |
| Start Compose services | `docker compose up -d` | Starts services in the background |
| Stop Compose services | `docker compose down` | Stops and removes Compose containers |
| View Compose logs | `docker compose logs -f` | Streams logs from Compose services |
| Remove unused Docker objects | `docker system prune` | Cleans unused containers, networks, and cache |

At the beginning, the most useful commands are:

```bash
docker ps
docker ps -a
docker images
docker logs -f NAME_OR_ID
docker compose up -d
docker compose down
```

## Why Docker Compose

For quick tests, `docker run` is fine.

For real local development, Docker Compose is usually better because the setup is written in a file. That means the environment can be saved, repeated, edited, reviewed, and version controlled.

Instead of running a long command manually, a `compose.yaml` file can define the service. The environment can then be started with:

```bash
docker compose up -d
```

And stopped with:

```bash
docker compose down
```

This is cleaner and more professional than relying on long one line commands.

## Project Folder

A simple local folder structure can look like this:

```bash
mkdir -p ~/Code/sqlserver-local
cd ~/Code/sqlserver-local
```

Inside it:

```text
sqlserver-local/
  compose.yaml
  .env
```

The `.env` file stores the password so that it is not hardcoded directly inside `compose.yaml`.

Example `.env`:

```env
MSSQL_SA_PASSWORD=YourStrongPassword123!
```

For real projects, `.env` should usually not be committed to Git.

## Running Microsoft SQL Server in Docker

The Compose file can look like this:

```yaml
services:
  sqlserver:
    image: mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest
    platform: linux/amd64
    container_name: sqlserver-local
    environment:
      ACCEPT_EULA: "Y"
      MSSQL_SA_PASSWORD: "${MSSQL_SA_PASSWORD}"
      MSSQL_PID: "Developer"
    ports:
      - "1433:1433"
    volumes:
      - sqlserver_data:/var/opt/mssql
    restart: unless-stopped

volumes:
  sqlserver_data:
```

The important parts are:

| Line | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| `image` | Uses the official Microsoft SQL Server image |
| `platform: linux/amd64` | Needed on Apple Silicon Macs because SQL Server image is AMD64 |
| `container_name` | Gives the container a readable name |
| `ACCEPT_EULA` | Accepts SQL Server license terms |
| `MSSQL_SA_PASSWORD` | Sets the administrator password |
| `MSSQL_PID: Developer` | Uses Developer edition for local development |
| `ports: "1433:1433"` | Makes SQL Server available on `localhost:1433` |
| `volumes` | Keeps database files after container restart |
| `restart: unless-stopped` | Restarts the container unless it is manually stopped |

Then the service can be started with:

```bash
docker compose up -d
```

Status can be checked with:

```bash
docker compose ps
```

Logs can be followed with:

```bash
docker compose logs -f
```

The key thing is to wait until SQL Server is ready for client connections.

## Apple Silicon Warning

On Apple Silicon Macs, SQL Server is not as native as PostgreSQL or many other containers. A common warning is:

```text
The requested image's platform (linux/amd64) does not match the detected host platform (linux/arm64/v8)
```

This means the Mac is ARM64, while the SQL Server image is AMD64.

The local fix is:

```yaml
platform: linux/amd64
```

This allows Docker to run the image through emulation. For learning and testing, that can be acceptable. For serious professional workloads, it is better to use a proper remote SQL Server, a company development database, or an x86 64 machine.

## Connecting with DBeaver

DBeaver can be used to connect to the SQL Server container.

Connection settings:

| Field | Value |
|---|---|
| Database type | Microsoft SQL Server |
| Host | `localhost` |
| Port | `1433` |
| Database | `master` |
| Username | `sa` |
| Password | Password from `.env` |
| Authentication | SQL Server Authentication |
| Trust server certificate | Enabled |

If the connection fails, the most common causes are:

| Problem | Fix |
|---|---|
| SQL Server is still starting | Wait and check logs |
| Wrong password | Check `.env` |
| Port conflict | Check if another service uses port `1433` |
| SSL or certificate error | Enable trust server certificate |
| Container stopped | Run `docker compose ps` and `docker compose logs -f` |

## Where SQL Server Stores Data

SQL Server is not like SQLite.

SQLite is usually one file:

```text
my_database.sqlite
```

SQL Server usually uses several files:

| File type | Example | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| Data file | `MyDb.mdf` | Tables, indexes, and data |
| Log file | `MyDb_log.ldf` | Transaction log |
| Additional data file | `MyDb_2.ndf` | Optional extra data file |

Inside the container, SQL Server stores files under:

```text
/var/opt/mssql/data/
```

But because the Compose file uses a Docker volume:

```yaml
volumes:
  - sqlserver_data:/var/opt/mssql
```

the data is persisted by Docker even if the container is removed.

That is an important point. Removing the container does not necessarily remove the database.

## Removing the Container

To stop and remove the SQL Server container while keeping the data volume:

```bash
docker compose down
```

This removes the container and network created by Compose, but keeps the volume.

If the service is started again:

```bash
docker compose up -d
```

the database files should still be there.

## Removing Everything

To remove the container and the volume with database files:

```bash
docker compose down -v
```

This is the clean reset command.

It removes:

```text
container
network
volume with SQL Server database files
```

After this, the local database data is gone.

## Removing the Downloaded SQL Server Image

The SQL Server image is the downloaded template. To remove it:

```bash
docker rmi mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest
```

This does not directly delete the database volume. It only removes the downloaded image.

The difference is:

| Command | Deletes |
|---|---|
| `docker compose down` | Container and network |
| `docker compose down -v` | Container, network, and database volume |
| `docker rmi mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest` | Downloaded SQL Server image |

So the cleanest full removal is:

```bash
docker compose down -v
docker rmi mcr.microsoft.com/mssql/server:2022-latest
```

## What This Shows

The most useful Docker lesson is that containers are disposable, but volumes are persistent.

That is exactly what makes Docker powerful. A local SQL Server can be created, tested, connected to from DBeaver, used by Python scripts, and removed when it is no longer needed.

For local development, this is much cleaner than installing every service directly into the operating system.

A reusable pattern is:

```text
Use local virtual environments for Python code.
Use Docker Compose for services.
Use volumes for data that should survive.
Use down -v only when a clean reset is really needed.
```

This is a simple but professional workflow. It makes experimentation safer while keeping the machine understandable.
